Impedance Coupling in Content-targeted Advertising 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:The current boom of the Web is associated with the revenues originated from on line advertising .
1-2:While search based advertising is dominant, the association of ads with a Web page (during user navigation) is becoming increasingly important .
1-3:In this work, we study the problem of associating ads with a Web page, referred to as content targeted advertising, from a computer science perspective .
1-4:We assume that we have access to the text of the Web page, the keywords declared by an advertiser, and a text associated with the advertiser"s business .
1-5:Using no other information and operating in fully automatic fashion, we propose ten strategies for solving the problem and evaluate their effectiveness .
1-6:Our methods indicate that a matching strategy that takes into account the semantics of the problem (referred to as AAK for ads and keywords) can yield gains in average precision figures of 60% compared to a trivial vector based strategy .
1-7:Further, a more sophisticated impedance coupling strategy, which expands the text of the Web page to reduce vocabulary impedance with regard to an advertisement, can yield extra gains in average precision of 50% .
1-8:These are first results .
1-9:They suggest that great accuracy in content targeted advertising can be attained with appropriate algorithms .
1-10:H.3.3 [Information Storage and Retrieval]: .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:The emergence of the Internet has opened up new marketing opportunities .
2-2:In fact, a company has now the possibility of showing its advertisements (ads) to millions of people at a low cost .
2-3:During the 90"s, many companies invested heavily on advertising in the Internet with apparently no concerns about their investment return [16] .
2-4:This situation radically changed in the following decade when the failure of many Web companies led to a dropping in supply of cheap venture capital and a considerable reduction in on line advertising investments [15,16] .
2-5:It was clear then that more effective strategies for on line advertising were required .
2-6:For that, it was necessary to take into account short term and long term interests of the users related to their information needs [9,14] .
2-7:As a consequence, many companies intensified the adoption of intrusive techniques for gathering information of users mostly without their consent [8] .
2-8:This raised privacy issues which stimulated the research for less invasive measures [16] .
2-9:More recently, Internet information gatekeepers as, for example, search engines, recommender systems, and comparison shopping services, have employed what is called paid placement strategies [3] .
2-10:In such methods, an advertiser company is given prominent positioning in advertisement lists in return for a placement fee .
2-11:Amongst these methods, the most popular one is a non intrusive technique called keyword targeted marketing [16] .
2-12:In this technique, keywords extracted from the user"s search query are matched against keywords associated with ads provided by advertisers .
2-13:A ranking of the ads, which also takes into consideration the amount that each advertiser is willing to pay, is computed .
2-14:The top ranked ads are displayed in the search result page together with the answers for the user query .
2-15:The success of keyword targeted marketing has motivated information gatekeepers to offer their advertisement services in different contexts .
2-16:For example, as shown in Figure 1, relevant ads could be shown to users directly in the pages of information portals .
2-17:The motivation is to take advantage of 496 the users immediate information interests at browsing time .
2-18:The problem of matching ads to a Web page that is browsed, which we also refer to as content targeted advertising [1], is different from that of keyword marketing .
2-19:In this case, instead of dealing with users" keywords, we have to use the contents of a Web page to decide which ads to display .
2-20:Figure 1: Example of content based advertising in the page of a newspaper .
2-21:The middle slice of the page shows the beginning of an article about the launch of a DVD movie .
2-22:At the bottom slice, we can see advertisements picked for this page by Google"s content based advertising system, AdSense .
2-23:It is important to notice that paid placement advertising strategies imply some risks to information gatekeepers .
2-24:For instance, there is the possibility of a negative impact on their credibility which, at long term, can demise their market share [3] .
2-25:This makes investments in the quality of ad recommendation systems even more important to minimize the possibility of exhibiting ads unrelated to the user"s interests .
2-26:By investing in their ad systems, information gatekeepers are investing in the maintenance of their credibility and in the reinforcement of a positive user attitude towards the advertisers and their ads [14] .
2-27:Further, that can translate into higher clickthrough rates that lead to an increase in revenues for information gatekeepers and advertisers, with gains to all parts [3] .
2-28:In this work, we focus on the problem of content targeted advertising .
2-29:We propose new strategies for associating ads with a Web page .
2-30:Five of these strategies are referred to as matching strategies .
2-31:They are based on the idea of matching the text of the Web page directly to the text of the ads and its associated keywords .
2-32:Five other strategies, which we here introduce, are referred to as impedance coupling strategies .
2-33:They are based on the idea of expanding the Web page with new terms to facilitate the task of matching ads and Web pages .
2-34:This is motivated by the observation that there is frequently a mismatch between the vocabulary of a Web page and the vocabulary of an advertisement .
2-35:We say that there is a vocabulary impedance problem and that our technique provides a positive effect of impedance coupling by reducing the vocabulary impedance .
2-36:Further, all our strategies rely on information that is already available to information gatekeepers that operate keyword targeted advertising systems .
2-37:Thus, no other data from the advertiser is required .
2-38:Using a sample of a real case database with over 93,000 ads and 100 Web pages selected for testing, we evaluate our ad recommendation strategies .
2-39:First, we evaluate the five matching strategies .
2-40:They match ads to a Web page using a standard vector model and provide what we may call trivial solutions .
2-41:Our results indicate that a strategy that matches the ad plus its keywords to a Web page, requiring the keywords to appear in the Web page, provides improvements in average precision figures of roughly 60% relative to a strategy that simply matches the ads to the Web page .
2-42:Such strategy, which we call AAK (for ads and keywords), is then taken as our baseline .
2-43:Following we evaluate the five impedance coupling strategies .
2-44:They are based on the idea of expanding the ad and the Web page with new terms to reduce the vocabulary impedance between their texts .
2-45:Our results indicate that it is possible to generate extra improvements in average precision figures of roughly 50% relative to the AAK strategy .
2-46:The paper is organized as follows .
2-47:In section 2, we introduce five matching strategies to solve content targeted advertising .
2-48:In section 3, we present our impedance coupling strategies .
2-49:In section 4, we describe our experimental methodology and datasets and discuss our results .
2-50:In section 5 we discuss related work .
2-51:In section 6 we present our conclusions. .
3 MATCHING STRATEGIES :
3-1:Keyword advertising relies on matching search queries to ads and its associated keywords .
3-2:Context based advertising, which we address here, relies on matching ads and its associated keywords to the text of a Web page .
3-3:Given a certain Web page p, which we call triggering page, our task is to select advertisements related to the contents of p .
3-4:Without loss of generality, we consider that an advertisement ai is composed of a title, a textual description, and a hyperlink .
3-5:To illustrate, for the first ad by Google shown in Figure 1, the title is Star Wars Trilogy Full, the description is Get this popular DVD free .
3-6:Free w free shopping .
3-7:Sign up now, and the hyperlink points to the site www.freegiftworld.com .
3-8:Advertisements can be grouped by advertisers in groups called campaigns, such that a campaign can have one or more advertisements .
3-9:Given our triggering page p and a set A of ads, a simple way of ranking ai ∈ A with regard to p is by matching the contents of p to the contents of ai .
3-10:For this, we use the vector space model [2], as discussed in the immediately following .
3-11:In the vector space model, queries and documents are represented as weighted vectors in an n dimensional space .
3-12:Let wiq be the weight associated with term ti in the query q and wij be the weight associated with term ti in the document dj .
3-13:Then, q = (w1q, w2q, ..., wiq, ..., wnq) and dj = (w1j, w2j, ..., wij, ..., wnj) are the weighted vectors used to represent the query q and the document dj .
3-14:These weights can be computed using classic tf idf schemes .
3-15:In such schemes, weights are taken as the product between factors that quantify the importance of a term in a document (given by the term frequency, or tf, factor) and its rarity in the whole collection (given by the inverse document factor, or idf, factor), see [2] for details .
3-16:The ranking of the query q with regard to the document dj is computed by the cosine similarity 497 formula, that is, the cosine of the angle between the two corresponding vectors: sim(q, dj) = q • dj |q| × |dj| = Pn i=1 wiq · wij qPn i=1 w2 iq qPn i=1 w2 ij (1) By considering p as the query and ai as the document, we can rank the ads with regard to the Web page p .
3-17:This is our first matching strategy .
3-18:It is represented by the function AD given by: AD(p, ai) = sim(p, ai) where AD stands for direct match of the ad, composed by title and description and sim(p, ai) is computed according to Eq .
3-19:(1) .
3-20:In our second method, we use other source of evidence provided by the advertisers: the keywords .
3-21:With each advertisement ai an advertiser associates a keyword ki, which may be composed of one or more terms .
3-22:We denote the association between an advertisement ai and a keyword ki as the pair (ai, ki) ∈ K, where K is the set of associations made by the advertisers .
3-23:In the case of keyword targeted advertising, such keywords are used to match the ads to the user queries .
3-24:In here, we use them to match ads to the Web page p .
3-25:This provides our second method for ad matching given by: KW(p, ai) = sim(p, ki) where (ai, ki) ∈ K and KW stands for match the ad keywords .
3-26:We notice that most of the keywords selected by advertisers are also present in the ads associated with those keywords .
3-27:For instance, in our advertisement test collection, this is true for 90% of the ads .
3-28:Thus, instead of using the keywords as matching devices, we can use them to emphasize the main concepts in an ad, in an attempt to improve our AD strategy .
3-29:This leads to our third method of ad matching given by: AD KW(p, ai) = sim(p, ai ∪ ki) where (ai, ki) ∈ K and AD KW stands for match the ad and its keywords .
3-30:Finally, it is important to notice that the keyword ki associated with ai could not appear at all in the triggering page p, even when ai is highly ranked .
3-31:However, if we assume that ki summarizes the main topic of ai according to an advertiser viewpoint, it can be interesting to assure its presence in p .
3-32:This reasoning suggests that requiring the occurrence of the keyword ki in the triggering page p as a condition to associate ai with p might lead to improved results .
3-33:This leads to two extra matching strategies as follows: ANDKW(p, ai) =  sim(p, ai) if ki p 0 if otherwise AD ANDKW(p, ai) = AAK(p, ai) =  sim(p, ai ∪ ki) if ki p 0 if otherwise where (ai, ki) ∈ K, ANDKW stands for match the ad keywords and force their appearance, and AD ANDKW (or AAK for ads and keywords) stands for match the ad, its keywords, and force their appearance .
3-34:As we will see in our results, the best among these simple methods is AAK .
3-35:Thus, it will be used as baseline for our impedance coupling strategies which we now discuss. .
4 IMPEDANCE COUPLING STRATEGIES :
4-1:Two key issues become clear as one plays with the contenttargeted advertising problem .
4-2:First, the triggering page normally belongs to a broader contextual scope than that of the advertisements .
4-3:Second, the association between a good advertisement and the triggering page might depend on a topic that is not mentioned explicitly in the triggering page .
4-4:The first issue is due to the fact that Web pages can be about any subject and that advertisements are concise in nature .
4-5:That is, ads tend to be more topic restricted than Web pages .
4-6:The second issue is related to the fact that, as we later discuss, most advertisers place a small number of advertisements .
4-7:As a result, we have few terms describing their interest areas .
4-8:Consequently, these terms tend to be of a more general nature .
4-9:For instance, a car shop probably would prefer to use car instead of super sport to describe its core business topic .
4-10:As a consequence, many specific terms that appear in the triggering page find no match in the advertisements .
4-11:To make matters worst, a page might refer to an entity or subject of the world through a label that is distinct from the label selected by an advertiser to refer to the same entity .
4-12:A consequence of these two issues is that vocabularies of pages and ads have low intersection, even when an ad is related to a page .
4-13:We cite this problem from now on as the vocabulary impedance problem .
4-14:In our experiments, we realized that this problem limits the final quality of direct matching strategies .
4-15:Therefore, we studied alternatives to reduce the referred vocabulary impedance .
4-16:For this, we propose to expand the triggering pages with new terms .
4-17:Figure 2 illustrates our intuition .
4-18:We already know that the addition of keywords (selected by the advertiser) to the ads leads to improved results .
4-19:We say that a keyword reduces the vocabulary impedance by providing an alternative matching path .
4-20:Our idea is to add new terms (words) to the Web page p to also reduce the vocabulary impedance by providing a second alternative matching path .
4-21:We refer to our expansion technique as impedance coupling .
4-22:For this, we proceed as follows .
4-23:expansion terms keyword vocabulary impedance triggering page p ad Figure 2: Addition of new terms to a Web page to reduce the vocabulary impedance .
4-24:An advertiser trying to describe a certain topic in a concise way probably will choose general terms to characterize that topic .
4-25:To facilitate the matching between this ad and our triggering page p, we need to associate new general terms with p .
4-26:For this, we assume that Web documents similar to the triggering page p share common topics .
4-27:Therefore, 498 by inspecting the vocabulary of these similar documents we might find good terms for better characterizing the main topics in the page p .
4-28:We now describe this idea using a Bayesian network model [10,11,13] depicted in Figure 3 .
