4-33:Figure 3: Bayesian network model for our impedance coupling technique .
4-34:In our model, which is based on the belief network in [11], the nodes represent pieces of information in the domain .
4-35:With each node is associated a binary random variable, which takes the value 1 to mean that the corresponding entity (a page or terms) is observed and, thus, relevant in our computations .
4-36:In this case, we say that the information was observed .
4-37:Node R represents the page r, a new representation for the triggering page p .
4-38:Let N be the set of the k most similar documents to the triggering page, including the triggering page p itself, in a large enough Web collection C .
4-39:Root nodes D0 through Dk represent the documents in N, that is, the triggering page D0 and its k nearest neighbors, D1 through Dk, among all pages in C .
4-40:There is an edge from node Dj to node R if document dj is in N .
4-41:Nodes T1 through Tm represent the terms in the vocabulary of C .
4-42:There is an edge from node Dj to a node Ti if term ti occurs in document dj .
4-43:In our model, the observation of the pages in N leads to the observation of a new representation of the triggering page p and to a set of terms describing the main topics associated with p and its neighbors .
4-44:Given these definitions, we can now use the network to determine the probability that a term ti is a good term for representing a topic of the triggering page p .
4-45:In other words, we are interested in the probability of observing the final evidence regarding a term ti, given that the new representation of the page p has been observed, P(Ti = 1|R = 1) .
