4-65:The set r is composed of the terms ti such that P (Ti|R) P (Ttop|R) ≥ β, where β is a given threshold .
4-66:In our experiments, we have used β = 0.05 .
4-67:Notice that the set r might contain terms that already occur in p .
4-68:That is, while we will refer to the set r as expansion terms, it should be clear that p ∩ r = ∅ .
4-69:By using α = 0, we simply consider the terms originally in page p .
4-70:By increasing α, we relax the context of the page p, adding terms from neighbor pages, turning page p into its new representation r .
4-71:This is important because, sometimes, a topic apparently not important in the triggering page offers a good opportunity for advertising .
4-72:For example, consider a triggering page that describes a congress in London about digital photography .
4-73:Although London is probably not an important topic in this page, advertisements about hotels in London would be appropriate .
4-74:Thus, adding hotels to page p is important .
4-75:This suggests using α > 0, that is, preserving the contents of p and using the terms in r to expand p .
4-76:In this paper, we examine both approaches .
4-77:Thus, in our sixth method we match r, the set of new expansion terms, directly to the ads, as follows: AAK T(p, ai) = AAK(r, ai) where AAK T stands for match the ad and keywords to the set r of expansion terms .
4-78:In our seventh method, we match an expanded page p to the ads as follows: AAK EXP(p, ai) = AAK(p ∪ r, ai) where AAK EXP stands for match the ad and keywords to the expanded triggering page .
4-79:499 To improve our ad placement methods, other external source that we can use is the content of the page h pointed to by the advertisement"s hyperlink, that is, its landing page .
4-80:After all, this page comprises the real target of the ad and perhaps could present a more detailed description of the product or service being advertised .
4-81:Given that the advertisement ai points to the landing page hi, we denote this association as the pair (ai, hi) ∈ H, where H is the set of associations between the ads and the pages they point to .
4-82:Our eighth method consists of matching the triggering page p to the landing pages pointed to by the advertisements, as follows: H(p, ai) = sim(p, hi) where (ai, hi) ∈ H and H stands for match the hyperlink pointed to by the ad .
4-83:We can also combine this information with the more promising methods previously described, AAK and AAK EXP as follows .
4-84:Given that (ai, hi) ∈ H and (ai, ki) ∈ K, we have our last two methods: AAK H(p, ai) =  sim(p, ai ∪ hi ∪ ki) if ki p 0 if otherwise AAK EXP H(p, ai) =  sim(p ∪ r, ai ∪ hi ∪ ki) if ki (p ∪ r) 0 if otherwise where AAK H stands for match ads and keywords also considering the page pointed by the ad and AAH EXP H stands for match ads and keywords with expanded triggering page, also considering the page pointed by the ad .
4-85:Notice that other combinations were not considered in this study due to space restrictions .
4-86:These other combinations led to poor results in our experimentation and for this reason were discarded. .
5 EXPERIMENTS :
5-1:4.1 Methodology To evaluate our ad placement strategies, we performed a series of experiments using a sample of a real case ad collection with 93,972 advertisements, 1,744 advertisers, and 68,238 keywords2 .
5-2:The advertisements are grouped in 2,029 campaigns with an average of 1.16 campaigns per advertiser .
5-3:For the strategies AAK T and AAK EXP, we had to generate a set of expansion terms .
5-4:For that, we used a database of Web pages crawled by the TodoBR search engine [12] (http: www.todobr.com.br ) .
5-5:This database is composed of 5,939,061 pages of the Brazilian Web, under the domain .br .
5-6:For the strategies H, AAK H, and AAK EXP H, we also crawled the pages pointed to by the advertisers .
5-7:No other filtering method was applied to these pages besides the removal of HTML tags .
5-8:Since we are initially interested in the placement of advertisements in the pages of information portals, our test collection was composed of 100 pages extracted from a Brazilian newspaper .
5-9:These are our triggering pages .
5-10:They were crawled in such a way that only the contents of their articles was preserved .
5-11:As we have no preferences for particular 2 Data in portuguese provided by an on line advertisement company that operates in Brazil .
5-12:topics, the crawled pages cover topics as diverse as politics, economy, sports, and culture .
5-13:For each of our 100 triggering pages, we selected the top three ranked ads provided by each of our 10 ad placement strategies .
5-14:Thus, for each triggering page we select no more than 30 ads .
5-15:These top ads were then inserted in a pool for that triggering page .
5-16:Each pool contained an average of 15.81 advertisements .
5-17:All advertisements in each pool were submitted to a manual evaluation by a group of 15 users .
5-18:The average number of relevant advertisements per page pool was 5.15 .
5-19:Notice that we adopted the same pooling method used to evaluate the TREC Web based collection [6] .
5-20:To quantify the precision of our results, we used 11 point average figures [2] .
5-21:Since we are not able to evaluate the entire ad collection, recall values are relative to the set of evaluated advertisements .
5-22:4.2 Tuning Idf factors We start by analyzing the impact of different idf factors in our advertisement collection .
5-23:Idf factors are important because they quantify how discriminative is a term in the collection .
5-24:In our ad collection, idf factors can be computed by taking ads, advertisers or campaigns as documents .
5-25:To exemplify, consider the computation of ad idf for a term ti that occurs 9 times in a collection of 100 ads .
5-26:Then, the inverse document frequency of ti is given by: idfi = log 100 9 Hence, we can compute ad, advertiser or campaign idf factors .
5-27:As we observe in Figure 4, for the AD strategy, the best ranking is obtained by the use of campaign idf, that is, by calculating our idf factor so that it discriminates campaigns .
5-28:Similar results were obtained for all the other methods .
5-29:0 0.05 0.1 0.15 0.2 0.25 0.3 0.35 0.4 0 0.2 0.4 0.6 0.8 1 precision recall Campaign idf Advertiser idf Ad idf Figure 4: Precision recall curves obtained for the AD strategy using ad, advertiser, and campaign idf factors .
5-30:This reflects the fact that terms might be better discriminators for a business topic than for an specific ad .
5-31:This effect can be accomplished by calculating the factor relative to idf advertisers or campaigns instead of ads .
5-32:In fact, campaign idf factors yielded the best results .
5-33:Thus, they will be used in all the experiments reported from now on .
5-34:500 4.3 Results Matching Strategies Figure 5 displays the results for the matching strategies presented in Section 2 .
5-35:As shown, directly matching the contents of the ad to the triggering page (AD strategy) is not so effective .
5-36:The reason is that the ad contents are very noisy .
5-37:It may contain messages that do not properly describe the ad topics such as requisitions for user actions (e.g, visit our site) and general sentences that could be applied to any product or service (e.g, we delivery for the whole country) .
5-38:On the other hand, an advertiser provided keyword summarizes well the topic of the ad .
5-39:As a consequence, the KW strategy is superior to the AD and AD KW strategies .
5-40:This situation changes when we require the keywords to appear in the target Web page .
5-41:By filtering out ads whose keywords do not occur in the triggering page, much noise is discarded .
5-42:This makes ANDKW a better alternative than KW .
5-43:Further, in this new situation, the contents of the ad becomes useful to rank the most relevant ads making AD ANDKW (or AAK for ads and keywords) the best among all described methods .
5-44:For this reason, we adopt AAK as our baseline in the next set of experiments .
